  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "Hottest GPUs in the 2026-03-01..2026-03-24 historical window are dominated by the k002-004-v* host group, all on GPU card 0, peaking at 82°C. A secondary set of warmer GPUs appears on k002-003 across multiple cards (2/4/6), but at lower temperatures (69–72°C).\n\nTop investigation targets (thermal risk):\n- k002-004-v5:8000 card0 (82°C)\n- k002-004-v7:8000 card0 (81°C)\n- k002-004-v1:8000 card0 (79°C)\nNext tier:\n- k002-004-v8:8000 card0 (76°C)\n- k002-004-v6:8000 card0 (75°C)\nComparator / lower urgency:\n- k002-003:8000 card4 (72°C), card2 (71°C), card6 (69°C)\n\nHost context and what it suggests: multiple distinct k002-004-v* nodes show top temperatures and all are card0. That pattern is consistent with (a) systematic workload placement skewing GPU0, (b) a shared cooling/airflow or fan-curve issue affecting that node group, or (c) incomplete per-card telemetry export.\n\nCorrelation limits: the preview only provides temperature for “hotGpusByTemperature”; it does not include GPU utilization, VRAM pressure, power draw, fan RPM, throttling indicators, or job-to-node placement, so “most stressed” can only be asserted thermally (not by activity) and workload attribution is ambiguous."
    ],
    "highlights": [
      "Hottest observed GPU: k002-004-v5:8000 card0 at 82°C (highest priority).",
      "Thermal outliers cluster on k002-004-v* and consistently on card0, pointing to possible GPU0 placement bias or systemic cooling/instrumentation effects.",
      "k002-003 has multiple warm GPUs (72/71/69°C) but is materially cooler than the k002-004-v* top set.",
      "Evidence gap: no utilization/VRAM/power/throttling metrics in the preview, so temperature cannot be reliably tied to “activity-driven” stress vs cooling deficiency."
